Keeper Platform Development Rules (v2.2 — August 2025)

This document is the canonical, in-repo source of truth for Keeper development.
It supersedes prior versions (including v2.0 / v2.1).
Cursor and all contributors must follow this file.

1) Architecture & Workspaces

Monorepo using pnpm workspaces
Workspaces: apps/*, packages/*, tools/*

apps/web — React + Vite (Vercel). Entry: src/main.tsx. JSX in src/**/*.tsx.

apps/api — Express (Railway). Entry: src/index.ts. Routes in src/routes/**, services in src/services/**.

packages/* — shared libs (types/ui/utils). Private by default.

Package manager: pnpm. Run from repo root. Use -F/--filter for per-app scripts.

Node target: 22.x recommended (CI/local). 20.x LTS acceptable if CI pins it.
Windows is supported; avoid shell pipes/globs that break on PowerShell.

2) Core Technologies

Frontend: React, TypeScript, Vite, Tailwind, shadcn/ui, lucide-react, framer-motion (as needed), react-router-dom.

Backend: Express + TypeScript, Prisma → Postgres (Railway).

Auth: KAM (Keeper Access Module) w/ JWT.

Theming: Media/Theme models; Keeper Classic default after resets. Seed more themes via seeds.

3) Environments & Deployment

Vercel for apps/web (monorepo-aware).

Railway for apps/api (env managed in Railway).

Branching: main (protected). Features feat/*, fixes fix/*, chores chore/*.

Releases: tag vX.Y.Z. Production deploys from tags or approved main.

4) Database & Prisma

Schema: apps/api/prisma/schema.prisma

Local dev:

pnpm -F keeper-api prisma:generate

pnpm -F keeper-api prisma:migrate:dev

Prod: pnpm -F keeper-api migrate:deploy

Seeders: idempotent; always (re)add canonical themes.

5) Environment Variables & Files

Required (API): DATABASE_URL, JWT_SECRET

Optional: REDIS_URL

Switches: DISABLE_REDIS=true forces no-Redis mode (dev/tests/local).

Defaults: NODE_ENV (development), LOG_LEVEL (sane default)

Do not hardcode secrets anywhere; never ship client-side.

Canonical filenames

Root example: ./.env.example (document all required and optional keys).

API test env: apps/api/.env.test (this exact name; used by Vitest).
Must not require real DB/Redis for smoke tests.

6) TypeScript, Build & Modules

strict: true; avoid any. Prefer unknown + narrowing.

Module system: pick per target and be consistent (NodeNext/ESM or CJS).
If ESM on backend, beware default import quirks (e.g., ioredis).

Path aliases supported via tsconfig; use Vite + tsconfig-paths (web) or ts-node/tsx helpers (api).

Outputs: web via Vite to dist; api via tsc to dist (or tsx in dev).

7) Redis Policy (Optional Cache/Queue)

Backend must run without Redis.

If DISABLE_REDIS=true, Redis wrappers no-op gracefully.

If REDIS_URL present and Redis is enabled, misconfig throws clear errors.

Tests that actually need Redis must be tagged and opt-in only (not part of smoke).

8) Linting & Formatting

ESLint + TypeScript plugin; Prettier at root (one config).

Keep noise manageable but visible:

@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any: warn

no-unused-vars and @typescript-eslint/no-unused-vars: off

unused-imports/no-unused-imports: error

unused-imports/no-unused-vars: warn with _-prefixed ignore

Web ESLint config must not be shadowed by root – make web’s config authoritative if needed (root: true) or consolidate into root flat config thoughtfully.

9) Logging & Errors

API: structured logs (JSON). Include requestId. Don’t log secrets.

Web: error boundaries for route roots; humane errors. Sentry optional (env-gated).

10) Security & KAM

KAM enforces domain/role policies; apply checks before returning private data.

CORS is domain-aware; no wildcard in prod.

Never expose secrets to the browser; use server endpoints.

11) UX Principles

Mobile-first; performance budget enforced.

Boards/Frames primitives: Dialog, Topics, Drafts, Tasks, Config, Activity.
MemoryFrame is nice-to-have, not MVP-blocking.

Studio flow: Capture → Connect → Create → Build; consistent theming.

12) AI & Kip

Kip = framework, not persona; agents are modular; MCP endpoints clean.

RAG/fine-tune hybrid planned; embeddings and data layers remain server-side.

13) CI/CD

CI validates: install → typecheck → lint → test → build (web+api) via pnpm filters.
Use Windows-safe commands in scripts (no pipes).

CD: deploy web (Vercel) & api (Railway) on tags/approved main.

14) The Balanced Loop (Ops Contract)

Why: Keep momentum and quality. One quick check per edit; a short smoke before commit.
Windows-safe. No shell pipes. No real infra needed.

Scripts (root package.json)

quick:web → pnpm -F keeper-web run type-check

quick:api → pnpm -F keeper-api run test:smoke

smoke:api → pnpm -F keeper-api run type-check && pnpm -F keeper-api run test --run

smoke:web → pnpm -F keeper-web run type-check && pnpm -F keeper-web run build

smoke → pnpm run smoke:api && pnpm run smoke:web

API smoke definition (minimal, infra-free)

apps/api/package.json:
test:smoke → vitest run --reporter=dot --silent --grep @smoke

At least one test file like:
apps/api/src/tests/smoke/basic.test.ts with a trivial @smoke test that does not touch DB/Redis.

How to use

After you edit API: pnpm run quick:api

After you edit WEB: pnpm run quick:web

Before commit/PR: pnpm run smoke

If your change truly touches DB/Redis, use a separate tagged test suite (e.g., @integration) and run it only when needed or in CI.

15) Local Bootstrap Runbook

pnpm install -w

If prompted: pnpm approve-builds (Prisma/esbuild/tailwind oxide, etc.)

Copy env template: cp .env.example .env (adjust per OS) and set server-side keys only.

API test env: create apps/api/.env.test containing minimal keys for smoke (must not require real DB/Redis).

Verify tooling:

pnpm -v (expect 10+)

node -v (prefer 22.x)

Sanity checks:

pnpm run quick:api

pnpm run quick:web

pnpm run smoke

Windows note: avoid |, grep, sed, cat, or complex globbing in scripts. Keep all commands plain.

16) Git/GitHub Workflow

Small PRs; one logical concern; ≤ 7 changed files target.

Link issues; screenshots for UI; schema diffs for DB changes.

≥ 1 review required. No direct pushes to main.

17) Definition of Done (DoD)

Local builds pass for changed targets.

pnpm run smoke green.

Lint/typecheck clean for changed files.

Tests updated/added for changed logic.

Docs updated (README, .env.example, CHANGELOG if user-visible).

Observability hooks where applicable.

18) PR Checklist (paste into PRs)

 Scope & acceptance criteria clear

 ≤ 1 logical concern; ≤ 7 files changed

 quick:* checks green for touched targets

 pnpm run smoke green

 Lint/typecheck clean (changed files)

 Tests updated/added

 DB migration safe & reversible (if any)

 Web build OK (Vercel), API build OK (Railway)

 Docs updated (README/.env.example)

 Screens/recording added (UI)

19) Release & Rollback

Tag semantic versions; maintain CHANGELOG.

Rollback: revert tag or redeploy previous artifact.

DB: apply down migrations only if safe.

20) Outstanding Compliance Expectations

Redis Optionality

Required: code path respects DISABLE_REDIS=true; no crashes without REDIS_URL.

Testing Infrastructure

Vitest present in API. @smoke suite must run without DB/Redis.

Heavier @integration tests are opt-in (dev/CI), not part of smoke.

CI/CD Workflow

CI runs install → typecheck → lint → test → build for web+api with filters.

Use Windows-safe commands in all scripts.

.env.example

Keep up to date at repo root with required (DATABASE_URL, JWT_SECRET) and optional (REDIS_URL, DISABLE_REDIS, NODE_ENV, LOG_LEVEL) keys.

Theme Seeding

Keep canonical seeds (Keeper Classic, Keen Kip, Lowcountry Summer, Juke Joint) idempotent.

21) Cursor Collaboration Rules

Always confirm monorepo context; operate at repo root; use pnpm filters.

Backend is Express (no Next.js in API).

Any Redis usage must keep DISABLE_REDIS=true path working.

Keep changes minimal & reversible; prefer small PRs.

If unsure, generate a brief Audit Report aligned with this doc before changing code.

